05277nam a2200901Ia 9783110760774DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20232023gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831107607747 a10.1515/97831107607742doi  a(DE-B1597)590072  a(OCoLC)1399539117  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aHB201b.C436 2023 7aBUS0690302bisacsh04a929.3742231 aChambers, Samuel A. , eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMoney Has No Value /cSamuel A. Chambers. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (IX, 211 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tAdvance praise -- tAcknowledgements -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tChapter One How to Do the Theory of Money -- tChapter Two The Matrix of Money Theories -- tChapter Three Money “Is” Credit -- tChapter Four Money Theories Today -- tChapter Five From Money/Credit to Money-Credit -- tChapter Six Money Markets -- tChapter Seven Money Today -- tBibliography0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWe need a new theory of money. The still-dominant theory of money as taught in intro textbooks is 100+ years old, and for almost that long we have known that it’s totally wrong. The best alternative are "heterodox" accounts developed in the 90s and 00s. These are indeed better overall descriptions of money, but they remain incomplete and inadequate: they rely too much on why the orthodoxy is wrong, thereby incorrectly assuming there is only one alternative (so-called heterodoxy). Money has no value develops a new (more subtle, more sophisticated) theory of money. It takes more seriously than any other work to date, the depth and seriousness of the fundamental claim that all money is credit. Money is not a thing, but a marker of a social relation of credit and debt between two parties. Money is not value itself; no form of money (as money) ever possesses any positive, intrinsic value. Second, the book shows that not only is all money credit, but that in an important theoretical sense, all credit is money to the extent any credit/debt between two parties has the potential to be transferred to another party (thereby functioning as money). Finally, the book links this radical credit theory of money to today’s concrete money practices: this includes global capital flows, national and international monetary policy, and most of all the daily turnover in the money markets. The book therefore develops the needed conceptual framework to ask questions like: what is going on with Bitcoin (much less GameStop) in 2021.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aExchange. 0aMoneyxHistory. 4aBrexit. 4aDemokratie. 4aGroßbritannien. 4aPolitik. 4aPopulismus. 4aVerfassung. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Economics / Theory.2bisacsh  acredit as money.  ahistory of money.  amoney as credit.  amoney markets.  atheory of money.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2023 Part 1z978311117578208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Business and Economics 2023 Englishz978311131907008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Economics 2023z9783111318134oZDB-23-DBV0 cEPUBz97831107967420 cprintz978311076072940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311076077440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110760774423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110760774/original  a978-3-11-117578-2  DG Plus DeG Package 2023 Part 1